{{Infobox aircraft occurrence |name = Olympic Airways Flight 954 |occurrence_type = Accident |image = Douglas DC-6B SX-DAI Olympic LHR 17.08.63 edited-2.jpg |image_size = 350px |alt = |caption = An Olympic Airways Douglas DC-6 similar to the accident aircraft |date = 8 December 1969 |type = [[Controlled flight into terrain]] (CFIT) |site = Near [[Keratea]], [[Greece]] |coordinates = <!--These 17 entries for single-aircraft occurrence:------> |aircraft_type = [[Douglas DC-6|Douglas DC-6B]] |aircraft_name = |operator = [[Olympic Airways]] |tail_number = SX-DAE |origin = [[Chania International Airport]] |stopover = |stopover0 = |stopover1 = |stopover2 = |stopover3 = |last_stopover = |destination = [[Ellinikon International Airport|Athens-Ellinikon International Airport]]| |passengers = 85 |crew = 5 |fatalities = 90 |survivors = 0 }} '''Olympic Airways Flight 954''' was a [[Douglas DC-6|Douglas DC-6B]] aircraft that crashed into a mountain near [[Keratea]] (approx. coordinates 37°48' N, 23°57' E), [[Greece]]. All 85 passengers and 5 crew on board died in the crash.
==The crash== The flight was a domestic scheduled passenger service from [[Chania]] on the island of [[Crete]] to [[Athens]]. While on approach to Athens and with its undercarriage retracted, the aircraft struck Mount Paneio at an altitude of approximately 2,000 feet. The weather at the time of the crash was characterized by rain and high winds.
The crash of Flight 954 was the deadliest aviation accident in Greek history at the time it took place, a record it maintained until the crash of [[Helios Airways Flight 522]] nearly thirty-six years later. It is still the deadliest aviation accident involving a Douglas DC-6.,<ref>[http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19691208-0 Aircraft accident Douglas DC-6B SX-DAE Athens]</ref> and deadliest crash in the history of Olympic Airways.
==Cause== It was ruled that the flight crew had deviated from the proper track and descended below the [[Lowest safe altitude|minimum safe altitude]] while making an [[Instrument landing system|ILS]] approach.<ref>{{cite book |title=Aviation Disasters Second Edition |last1=Gero |first1=David |publisher=Patrick Stephens Limited |year= 1996 |page=91 }}</ref>
